[{"location":"api/#Structs","page":"API","title":"Structs","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Functions","page":"API","title":"Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Plotting","page":"API","title":"Plotting","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#SignalDetectionModels.SDT","page":"API","title":"SignalDetectionModels.SDT","text":"SDT{T <: Real} <: AbstractSDT\n\nFields\n\nd::T: discriminability\nc::T: criterion relative optimal value\nσₛ::T: standard deviation of noise distribution \nnₙ::Int: number of noise trials\nnₛ::Int: number of signal trials\n\nConstructors\n\nSDT(; d, c, σₛ = 1.0, nₙ, nₛ = nₙ)\n\nSDT(d, c, σₛ, nₙ, nₛ)\n\nReferences\n\nStanislaw, H., & Todorov, N. (1999). Calculation of signal detection theory measures.  Behavior research methods, instruments, & computers, 31(1), 137-149.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#SignalDetectionModels.compute_c","page":"API","title":"SignalDetectionModels.compute_c","text":"compute_c(model::AbstractSDT)\n\nComputes criterion c. \n\nArguments\n\nmodel::AbstractSDT: abstract signal detection theory model \n\n\n\n\n\ncompute_c(hr::Real, far::Real, σₛ = 1.0)\n\nComputes criterion c. \n\nArguments\n\nhr::Real: hit rate \nfar::Real: false alarm rate \nσₛ = 1.0: standard deviation of the signal distribution \n\nExample\n\nusing SignalDetectionModels\nhr = .90\nfar = .05\ncompute_c(hr, far)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SignalDetectionModels.compute_d","page":"API","title":"SignalDetectionModels.compute_d","text":"compute_d(model::AbstractSDT)\n\nComputes discriminability d. \n\nArguments\n\nmodel::AbstractSDT: abstract signal detection theory model \n\n\n\n\n\ncompute_d(hr::Real, far::Real, σₛ = 1.0)\n\nComputes discriminability d. \n\nArguments\n\nhr::Real: hit rate \nfar::Real: false alarm rate \nσₛ = 1.0: standard deviation of the signal distribution \n\nExample\n\nusing SignalDetectionModels\nhr = .90\nfar = .05\ncompute_d(hr, far)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SignalDetectionModels.compute_far","page":"API","title":"SignalDetectionModels.compute_far","text":"compute_far(model::AbstractSDT)\n\nComputes false alarm rate. \n\nArguments\n\nmodel::AbstractSDT: abstract signal detection theory model \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SignalDetectionModels.compute_hr","page":"API","title":"SignalDetectionModels.compute_hr","text":"compute_hr(model::AbstractSDT)\n\nComputes hit rate. \n\nArguments\n\nmodel::AbstractSDT: abstract signal detection theory model \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#Distributions.logpdf","page":"API","title":"Distributions.logpdf","text":"logpdf(model::AbstractSDT, data::Vector{Int})\n\nCompute log likelihood of data based on signal detection theory model.   \n\nArguments\n\nmodel::AbstractSDT: abstract signal detection theory model \ndata::Vector{Int}: data vector containing the hit count and false alarm count\n\nExample\n\nusing SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = 0.0, nₙ = 100)\ndata = rand(model)\nLL = logpdf(model, data)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#Base.rand","page":"API","title":"Base.rand","text":"rand(model::AbstractSDT)\n\nGenerates simulated data from model. \n\nArguments\n\nmodel::AbstractSDT: abstract signal detection theory model \n\nReturns\n\ndata::Vector{Int}: data vector containing the hit count and false alarm count\n\nExample\n\nusing SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = 0.0, nₙ = 100)\ndata = rand(model)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#SignalDetectionModels.plot_distributions","page":"API","title":"SignalDetectionModels.plot_distributions","text":"plot_distributions(\n    model::AbstractSDT;\n    far_color = RGB(99/255, 144/255, 166/255),\n    hr_color = RGB(67 / 255, 97 / 255, 112 / 255),\n    config...\n)\n\nGenerates a plot of a noise and signal distribution with the criterion represented as a vertical line. \n\nArguments\n\nmodel::AbstractSDT: an abstract signal detection theory model \n\nKeywords\n\nfar_color = RGB(99/255, 144/255, 166/255): the color of the false alarm rate of the noise distribution \nhr_color = RGB(67 / 255, 97 / 255, 112 / 255): the color of hit rate area of the signal distribution\nconfig...: optional keyword arguments to configure plot\n\nExample\n\nusing SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = .50, σₛ = 1.5, nₙ = 100)\nplot_distributions(model)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"basic_usage/#Overview","page":"Basic Usage","title":"Overview","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"basic_usage/#Create-Model","page":"Basic Usage","title":"Create Model","text":"using SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = 0.0, nₙ = 100)","category":"section"},{"location":"basic_usage/#Generate-Data","page":"Basic Usage","title":"Generate Data","text":"data = rand(model)","category":"section"},{"location":"basic_usage/#Log-Likelihood","page":"Basic Usage","title":"Log Likelihood","text":"LL = logpdf(model, data)","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Overview","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Overview","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Full-Code","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Full Code","text":"You can reveal copy-and-pastable version of the full code by clicking the ▶ below.\n\n<details>\n<summary><b>Show Full Code</b></summary>\n\nusing Distributions\nusing Mooncake\nusing Random\nusing SignalDetectionModels\nusing StatsPlots\nusing Turing \n\nRandom.seed!(2185)\nn_subj = 100\nnₙ = 100\n\nparms = map(1:n_subj) do _ \n    d = rand(Normal(0, 1))\n    c = rand(Normal(0, 1))\n    (;d, c, nₙ)\nend\n\ndata = map(Θ -> rand(SDT(; Θ...)), parms)\n\n@model function turing_model(data, nₙ)\n    n_subj = length(data)\n    # mean of group-level discriminability  \n    μd ~ Normal(0, 1)\n    # SD of group-level discriminability \n    σd ~ Gamma(2, 1)\n    d ~ filldist(Normal(μd, σd), n_subj)\n    # mean of group-level criterion  \n    μc ~ Normal(0, 1)\n    # SD of group-level criterion \n    σc ~ Gamma(2, 1)\n    c ~ filldist(Normal(μc, σc), n_subj)\n    for i ∈ 1:n_subj\n        data[i] ~ SDT(; d = d[i], c = c[i], nₙ)\n    end\nend\n\n# adtype = AutoForwardDiff()\nadtype = AutoMooncake()\n\nchains = sample(turing_model(data, nₙ), NUTS(1000, 0.65; adtype), MCMCThreads(), 1000, 4)\ngroup_chains = chains[:, [:μd, :μc, :σd, :σc],:]\ndescribe(group_chains)\nplot(group_chains)\n\n</details>","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Load-Dependencies","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Load Dependencies","text":"using Distributions\nusing Mooncake\nusing Random\nusing SignalDetectionModels\nusing StatsPlots\nusing Turing ","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Model-Configuration","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Model Configuration","text":"Random.seed!(2185)\nn_subj = 100\nnₙ = 100","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Generate-Subject-Level-Parameters","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Generate Subject-Level Parameters","text":"parms = map(1:n_subj) do _ \n    d = rand(Normal(0, 1))\n    c = rand(Normal(0, 1))\n    (;d, c, nₙ)\nend","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Generate-Simulated-Data","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Generate Simulated Data","text":"@model function turing_model(data, nₙ)\n    n_subj = length(data)\n    # mean of group-level discriminability  \n    μd ~ Normal(0, 1)\n    # SD of group-level discriminability \n    σd ~ Gamma(2, 1)\n    d ~ filldist(Normal(μd, σd), n_subj)\n    # mean of group-level criterion  \n    μc ~ Normal(0, 1)\n    # SD of group-level criterion \n    σc ~ Gamma(2, 1)\n    c ~ filldist(Normal(μc, σc), n_subj)\n    for i ∈ 1:n_subj\n        data[i] ~ SDT(; d = d[i], c = c[i], nₙ)\n    end\nend","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Estimate-Parameters","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Estimate Parameters","text":"chains = sample(turing_model(data, nₙ), NUTS(1000, 0.65; adtype = AutoMooncake()), MCMCThreads(), 1000, 4)\ngroup_chains = chains[:, [:μd, :μc, :σd, :σc],:]\ndescribe(group_chains)\n\n\nChains MCMC chain (1000×4×4 Array{Float64, 3}):\n\nIterations        = 1001:1:2000\nNumber of chains  = 4\nSamples per chain = 1000\nWall duration     = 17.12 seconds\nCompute duration  = 54.87 seconds\nparameters        = μd, σd, μc, σc\ninternals         = \n\nSummary Statistics\n\n  parameters      mean       std      mcse    ess_bulk    ess_tail      rhat   ess_per_sec \n      Symbol   Float64   Float64   Float64     Float64     Float64   Float64       Float64 \n\n          μd    0.1339    0.1090    0.0016   4488.5820   3268.4618    0.9995       81.8069\n          σd    1.0701    0.0831    0.0013   4417.6982   3199.9839    0.9998       80.5150\n          μc    0.1178    0.0977    0.0015   4449.0158   2827.2720    1.0014       81.0858\n          σc    0.9674    0.0712    0.0011   4575.8835   3487.0255    1.0006       83.3980\n\n\nQuantiles\n\n  parameters      2.5%     25.0%     50.0%     75.0%     97.5% \n      Symbol   Float64   Float64   Float64   Float64   Float64 \n\n          μd   -0.0753    0.0637    0.1346    0.2039    0.3544\n          σd    0.9230    1.0112    1.0659    1.1219    1.2496\n          μc   -0.0762    0.0530    0.1192    0.1822    0.3084\n          σc    0.8428    0.9173    0.9626    1.0119    1.1205","category":"section"},{"location":"hierarchical_model/#Plot-Group-Level-Posterior-Distributions","page":"Hierarchical Model","title":"Plot Group-Level Posterior Distributions","text":"plot(group_chains)\n\n(Image: )","category":"section"},{"location":"#SignalDetectionModels.jl","page":"Home","title":"SignalDetectionModels.jl","text":"This package provides basic functionality for applying and analyzing signal detection theory to data. Please navigate the menu on the left to learn more. ","category":"section"},{"location":"#References","page":"Home","title":"References","text":"Stanislaw, H., & Todorov, N. (1999). Calculation of signal detection theory measures.  Behavior Research Methods, Instruments, & Computers, 31(1), 137-149.\n\nd'etectable interactive tutorial","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Plot-Distributions","page":"Plotting","title":"Plot Distributions","text":"using SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = .50, σₛ = 1.5, nₙ = 100)\nplot_distributions(model)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Plot-ROC","page":"Plotting","title":"Plot ROC","text":"using SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = 1, σₛ = 1, nₙ = 100)\nplot_ROC(model)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Plot-zROC","page":"Plotting","title":"Plot zROC","text":"using SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = 1, σₛ = 1, nₙ = 100)\nplot_zROC(model)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Plot-iso-bias","page":"Plotting","title":"Plot iso-bias","text":"using SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = 1, σₛ = 1.5, nₙ = 100)\nplot_distributions(model)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Plot-iso-discriminability","page":"Plotting","title":"Plot iso-discriminability","text":"using SignalDetectionModels\nmodel = SDT(; d = 2.0, c = 1, σₛ = 1.5, nₙ = 100)\nplot_distributions(model)","category":"section"}]
